  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the US\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n- Limited regulatory framework\n\n2. International Developments\n- FATF established in 1989\n- Developed global anti-money laundering standards\n- Created recommendations for financial institutions\n- Encouraged international cooperation\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- US Patriot Act (2001)\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Expanded financial institution obligations\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Modern Regulatory Approaches\n- Enhanced customer due diligence\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Risk-based assessment frameworks\n- Comprehensive transaction monitoring\n\n5. Technological Integration\n- Digital transaction tracking\n- Advanced data analytics\n- Artificial intelligence for suspicious activity detection\n- Real-time monitoring systems\n\n6. Global Coordination\n- Increased cross-border information sharing\n- Unified regulatory standards\n- Collaborative enforcement mechanisms\n\n7. Emerging Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Blockchain transparency requirements\n- Enhanced digital financial crime prevention\n\nThe legislation continues to adapt to technological and financial innovations.",
